{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"alias":"woeful-frail-bufeo","description":"## What\n\nThe `README.md` quickstart (lines ~33-53) claims to \"Run one ticket end-to-end\nacross all three surfaces\" but does not: the CLI block creates a ticket then acts on\nan unrelated hard-coded id `reel-lot-tea`; the Python block creates a **separate**\nticket; the MCP block shows only client `mcpServers` config and performs no\noperation. This misleads every audience about how rebar actually works.\n\n## Scope\n\nPick ONE of two honest fixes (decide in a comment on this ticket, then implement):\n- **(preferred) Make it genuinely end-to-end**: capture the created id from the CLI\n  `create` (e.g. via `--output json` / an alias variable) and thread that SAME ticket\n  through the CLI, Python, and an actual MCP tool call; OR\n- **Retitle + reframe** the section to \"independent per-surface examples\" so the copy\n  matches what the blocks really do, and drop the \"one ticket end-to-end\" claim.\n\nPrefer the first if a stable, copy-pasteable capture pattern exists; otherwise the\nsecond. Whichever is chosen, the MCP block must either perform a real operation or the\nprose must stop implying it does.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] The quickstart's heading/claim matches what the code blocks actually do.\n- [ ] No hard-coded id (`reel-lot-tea`) that is disconnected from a just-created\n      ticket remains in a block that implies continuity.\n- [ ] If kept as \"end-to-end,\" the same ticket id flows across the surfaces and the\n      block is exercised by the golden-path CI smoke (see sibling CI ticket).\n\nFiles: `README.md` (lines ~33-53).","id":"b55f-639d-b4bd-4222","parent_id":"4191-b4f9-146a-43cd","priority":1,"tags":["docs","p0"],"ticket_type":"task","title":"P0: Repair README quickstart into a real end-to-end run"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1783814561898717001,"uuid":"cf93b36a-ebfe-4dd7-b613-23820c759e4c"}